The present invention is illustrated by way of example, and not by limitation, in the figures of the accompanying drawings, wherein elements having the same reference numeral designations represent like elements throughout and wherein:


FIG. 1A is a perspective view of the male and female portions of a fiber optic connector constructed according to the teachings of the present invention, shown in an uncoupled position;


FIG. 1B is a perspective view of the male and female portions of the fiber optic connector in a coupled position;


FIG. 2A is a side cross-sectional elevational view of the female portion of the connector;


FIG. 2B is a front elevational view of the female portion of the connector shown in FIG. 2A;


FIG. 3A is a side cross-sectional elevational view of the male portion of the connector;


FIG. 3B is a front elevational view of the male portion of the connector shown in FIG. 3A;


FIG. 4A is a side cross-sectional perspective view showing the shutters of the male and female portions of the connector before mating;


FIG. 4B is a side perspective cross-sectional elevational view of the shutters of the male and female portions of the connector shown in a mated position;


FIG. 4C is a side view of a cam and cam-follower which may be used to control opening of the shutters;


FIG. 5 is a side elevational view partially in cross-section showing the male and female portions of the connector prior to completion of mating of the male and female portions;


FIG. 5A is a side view of male and female optical contacts which may be used in the disclosed invention;


FIG. 6A is a front view of the shutter mechanism when the shutter is closed over the optical contacts in the female half of the connector; and


FIG. 6B is a front view showing the shutter in an open position to expose the optical contacts in the female half of the connector.
